{{! /freestyle/history — editorial history, pioneers, eras }}

<div class="hero hero-sm">
  <div>
    {{#if navigation.breadcrumbs}}
    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      {{#each navigation.breadcrumbs}}
        {{#if href}}<a href="{{href}}">{{label}}</a> <span class="breadcrumb-sep">/</span> {{else}}<span>{{label}}</span>{{/if}}
      {{/each}}
    </nav>
    {{/if}}
    <h1>{{page.title}}</h1>
    {{#if page.intro}}<p class="hero-subtitle">{{page.intro}}</p>{{/if}}
  </div>
</div>

<div class="wrapper">

  {{! ── Hero/intro media panel ──────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  {{#if content.heroMedia}}
  <section class="content-section history-media history-media--hero">
    {{#if content.heroMedia.media}}
    <div class="video-embed">
      {{> video-facade media=content.heroMedia.media}}
    </div>
    {{/if}}
    {{#if content.heroMedia.caption}}<p class="history-media-caption">{{content.heroMedia.caption}}</p>{{/if}}
    {{#if content.heroMedia.placeholderNote}}<p class="history-media-placeholder">{{content.heroMedia.placeholderNote}}</p>{{/if}}
  </section>
  {{/if}}

  {{! ── Two-Phase Story (opening framing, 2026-05-17) ───────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>The Two-Phase Story</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      Freestyle footbag has two distinct histories. The first is
      <strong>vocabulary building</strong> &mdash; roughly 1985 to 2008, the years
      in which the named tricks, the family structures, and the modifier
      conventions were established by a generation of innovators. The second
      is <strong>vocabulary maturation</strong> &mdash; 2008 to today, the years
      in which that vocabulary was deepened, recombined, and pushed against
      the limits of human biomechanics, without fundamentally new trick
      structures emerging.
    </p>
    <p>
      The competitive sport reflects both phases. Early-era players invented
      the language; modern-era players write longer, more layered sentences in
      it. The <a href="/freestyle/glossary#run-quality">ADD scoring system</a>
      encodes the difficulty of those sentences additively &mdash; a base
      trick's value plus the value of each modifier layered on top. Today's
      ADD-22 sequences and modern modifier-stacking architectures are the
      natural extensions of structures that took three decades to build.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Competitive Eras ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Competitive Eras</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Five overlapping chapters in the sport's competitive life &mdash; each shaped by
        the players, technology, and cultural energy of its time.
      </p>
    </div>
    {{#each content.eras}}
    <div class="history-era">
      <h3>{{period}} — {{label}}</h3>
      <p>{{summary}}</p>
      {{#if keyFigures.length}}
      <p class="detail-muted">Key figures: {{#each keyFigures}}{{#unless @first}}, {{/unless}}{{this}}{{/each}}</p>
      {{/if}}
    </div>
    {{/each}}
  </section>

  {{! ── Evolution of Difficulty ────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Evolution of Difficulty</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        A more focused lens on the same history: how the sport's working
        difficulty grammar grew, decade by decade.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="evolution-strip">
      {{#each content.evolution}}
      <div class="evolution-card">
        <div class="evolution-period">{{period}}</div>
        <h3 class="evolution-label">{{label}}</h3>
        <p>{{summary}}</p>
      </div>
      {{/each}}
    </div>
  </section>

  {{! ── How combos grew ───────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>How Combos Grew</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The story of how multi-trick sequences evolved from isolated kicks
        into the linked, density-driven runs that define modern competition.
      </p>
    </div>
    {{#each content.comboEvolution}}<p>{{this}}</p>{{/each}}
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Run-quality terms used here &mdash; <strong>guiltless</strong>, <strong>fearless</strong>,
      <strong>density</strong> &mdash; are defined in the
      <a href="/freestyle/glossary#run-quality">glossary's run-quality section</a>. The
      <em>modifier stacking</em> vocabulary the prose discusses is anchored in the
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=movement-system">movement-system browse view</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="history-combo-architecture-note">
      The vocabulary players use to talk about combos &mdash; <em>setup tricks</em>,
      <em>resolution tricks</em>, <em>recovery patterns</em>,
      <em>concentration vs breadth</em>, <em>launch nodes</em> and <em>attractors</em>
      &mdash; emerged from this period as players started to think about runs
      structurally rather than as random collections of hard tricks.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── From routines to guiltless: how judging evolved ──────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>From Routines to Guiltless: How Judging Evolved</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        Why a 1985 freestyle routine and a 2025 fearless run can both be the
        peak of their era — and how the language for "good" expanded along the way.
      </p>
    </div>
    {{#each content.earlyRoutineEvolution}}<p>{{this}}</p>{{/each}}
    <p class="detail-muted">
      See the <a href="/freestyle/glossary#run-quality">run-quality vocabulary</a>
      for the definitions of Tiltless, Guiltless, Tripless, Fearless, Beastly, and Godly.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Pioneers ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Founders &amp; Pioneers</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="section-intro">
      The early BAP (Big ADD Posse) inductees of the early 1990s were establishing
      freestyle's visual identity, trick taxonomy, and competition culture in the
      years before the ADD table was widely standardized. They built the language
      the sport still speaks — and the contests, friendships, and recordings that
      kept it alive.
    </p>

    {{#if content.pioneersMedia}}
    <div class="history-media history-media--pioneers">
      {{#if content.pioneersMedia.media}}
      <div class="video-embed">
        {{> video-facade media=content.pioneersMedia.media}}
      </div>
      {{/if}}
      {{#if content.pioneersMedia.caption}}<p class="history-media-caption">{{content.pioneersMedia.caption}}</p>{{/if}}
      {{#if content.pioneersMedia.placeholderNote}}<p class="history-media-placeholder">{{content.pioneersMedia.placeholderNote}}</p>{{/if}}
    </div>
    {{/if}}
    <div class="records-table-wrap">
      <table class="records-table records-table-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Player</th>
            <th>Contribution</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.pioneers}}
          <tr>
            <td>
              {{#if profileHref}}
                <a href="{{profileHref}}">{{name}}</a>
              {{else}}
                {{name}}
              {{/if}}
              {{#if recognitions.length}}
              {{#each recognitions}}<span class="pioneer-recognition" title="Recognition: {{this}}">{{this}}</span>{{/each}}
              {{/if}}
            </td>
            <td>{{note}}</td>
          </tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  {{! ── ADD System ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>The ADD System</h2>
    </div>
    {{#each content.addSystem}}
    <p>{{this}}</p>
    {{/each}}
    <p class="history-add-system-decomposition-note">
      ADD treats a trick as a decomposable structure. The system assigns
      a weight to each base trick and to each modifier; the total is the
      sum. This isn't just a scoring convention &mdash; it's the same logic
      that lets the dictionary describe a compound trick like
      <em>mobius</em> as "gyro torque" and have the ADD add up (4 + 1 = 5).
    </p>
    <p>
      See the <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a> for ADD values and modifier relationships,
      and <a href="/freestyle/insights">Freestyle Insights</a> for data-driven difficulty analysis.
      For a mechanical walkthrough of how ADD values are constructed, with worked examples
      and discrepancy case studies, see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Regional Shift ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>The Geographic Shift</h2>
    </div>
    <p>{{content.regionalShift}}</p>
    <p>
      See <a href="/freestyle/competition">Freestyle Competition</a> for podium counts and career records.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Modern Era ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>The Modern Game</h2>
    </div>
    <p>{{content.modernEra}}</p>

    {{#if content.modernEraMedia}}
    <div class="history-media history-media--modern">
      {{#if content.modernEraMedia.media}}
      <div class="video-embed">
        {{> video-facade media=content.modernEraMedia.media}}
      </div>
      {{/if}}
      {{#if content.modernEraMedia.caption}}<p class="history-media-caption">{{content.modernEraMedia.caption}}</p>{{/if}}
      {{#if content.modernEraMedia.placeholderNote}}<p class="history-media-placeholder">{{content.modernEraMedia.placeholderNote}}</p>{{/if}}
    </div>
    {{/if}}
  </section>

  {{! ── Movement Language as the Modern Vocabulary (closing framing, 2026-05-17) ──
      Frames the platform's recent formal-language work as the natural
      modern phase of the same vocabulary the early players built. }}
  <section class="content-section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Movement Language as the Modern Vocabulary</h2>
    </div>
    <p>
      The competitive sport's evolution has been mirrored by the maturation of
      its <em>vocabulary</em>. Today freestyle is documented across four formal
      layers: the <strong>canonical</strong>
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks">trick dictionary</a> (which tricks exist and
      what their ADD values are), the <strong>educational</strong>
      <a href="/freestyle/glossary">glossary</a> (what each trick means and how
      it relates to others), the <strong>symbolic</strong> layer of named
      compounds and equivalence chains (<em>mobius = gyro torque</em>), and the
      <strong>operational</strong> notation that compresses a trick to its
      structural skeleton (<em>paradox = CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX]</em>).
    </p>
    <p>
      These layers describe the same sport at different levels of analysis
      &mdash; a movement that was originally inherited as kinesthetic practice
      and is now legible to readers who weren't present when it was being
      built. The continued refinement of this language is its own form of
      evolution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <p class="source-note">
    Based on analysis of 774 documented competitive events (1980&ndash;2026) and 395 Sick 3 format sequences.
    Player descriptions draw from competition records and community documentation.
  </p>

</div>
